  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3367724248" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3367724248" />
    <a title="Michelle Woodstuff" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/75823393-michelle-woodstuff"><img alt="Michelle Woodstuff" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3367724248?book_show_action=true">May 31, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Michelle Woodstuff" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Michelle Woodstuff" href="/user/show/75823393-michelle-woodstuff">Michelle Woodstuff</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Mass Market Paperback " href="/book/show/9881740-the-lost-years-of-merlin">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3367724248" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12482278431405707341">This is a nice fantasy jaunt into a different take of the legend of Merlin.<br/><br/>The story begins in Wales at Caer Vedwyd, where a boy named Emrys lives in a shack, with an older woman called Branwen. Emrys has lost his memory and only knows that he and Branwen came from somewhere else. Somewhere that is not Wales. Emrys, remembering nothing of before, is determined to find himself and his true name.<br/><br/>After blundering into his first use of magic, drastically impairing himself, he sets out to places unkn</span>
  <span id="freeText12482278431405707341" style="display:none">This is a nice fantasy jaunt into a different take of the legend of Merlin.<br /><br />The story begins in Wales at Caer Vedwyd, where a boy named Emrys lives in a shack, with an older woman called Branwen. Emrys has lost his memory and only knows that he and Branwen came from somewhere else. Somewhere that is not Wales. Emrys, remembering nothing of before, is determined to find himself and his true name.<br /><br />After blundering into his first use of magic, drastically impairing himself, he sets out to places unknown. He lands in the dying realm of Fincayra where he makes friends with a woodland girl and a small giant. Together they seek to end the blight on the land by ending the reign of the mad king.<br /><br />I enjoyed the book immensely. It is definitely geared toward a younger audience and is very wholesome. It is reminiscent of a Tolkienesque style, but is clearly told in a different, more modern style. The main characters are virtuous, valiant, and seek to do good, but retain a complexity that kept me invested in their fates. <br /><br />In terms of Arthurian lore, it seems nicely based in both the real world and in another world, which is something I feel not many Arthurian writers do, at least in my experience. Most writers do touch Avalon, maintaining it's magic and wonder. Barron, however, has created his own magical land that is not Atlantis (as is part of some Arthurian legends) and is not Avalon. The fact that it is different is refreshing.<br /><br />The isle of Fincayra is wonderfully crafted, but the reader is never bogged down with too much information told in a dictionary form. The reader learns with Emrys, as his meets new people and is exposed to new cultures. It maintains an heir of mysticism, that makes me want to learn more about the magic, the creatures, and the people of this world.<br /><br />A big drawback for me is the episodic nature of the chapters. It almost progresses, especially once Emrys arrives on Fincayra, like each chapter is a new episode in a Television series. In one chapter they defeat a shapeshifter, in another they talk to a spider, in the next chapter they find goblins, in a later chapter they encounter an old married couple, and in another they meet a man who likes to read, and in another they best a peculiar woman who likes to gamble. This is not to say that these events were not entertaining to experience, but rarely did it feel like they were necessary. It did not seem that the characters underwent much character development, despite the hardships they faced. <br />A lot of what happened in the book seemed unrelated to the climax and conclusion of the story. <br /><br />Another drawback is that many of Emrys's questions about himself were too easily resolved at the end of the book. Understanding that this is the first in a series of books, I did not expect Emrys to even begin to grasp who he was until the next installment and then, only little. Instead he learns of his father, his mother, and seemingly regains his memory. The defeat of the villain and the history Emrys has with him, felt too neat and similar to many other stories. The twist was not as twisty as I would have liked. Or I wish the twist was explored over a greater length of time and not just at the conclusion of the book.<br /><br />Overall I would recommend it to others, particularly parents of children and general fans of the fantasy genre who are craving a pleasant, wholesome read that depicts the heroic struggle between good and evil. I look forward to reading the next installment.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12482278431405707341" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

